div.div:
Similarity graphs using interface structures
(embedded variables on supporting/interface structures, an embedded variable representing a more trivial change and each supporting/interface structure representing a variable and a connection to another variable)
These similarity-interface graphs are useful to frame similarity/difference units, which can be combined and compared more easily.
A similar similarity-interface graph would have similar info content (meaning it would encode similar info/variation).
When all of the supporting variables of the highest amount of variation are identified, those are the primary interface variables, such as truth, logic, etc. This can be applied in reverse, building higher variation variables from lower variation variables that can be embedded on it, until each sequence encapsulates the maximum variation it can (without changing its default embedding interaction structure or changing any variables or their interactions).
Once structured in this way, useful queries are possible, such as 'find structures that build similarly high variation as this set of structures' to 'find equivalent alternate variables' or 'find complementary variables across high-variation variables'.
Other graphs can be constructed from these structures, like network graphs of these structures which indicate useful similarities/differences, like 'different embeddings of similar variables on different interface structures' (sub-networks or sub-sequences of variable variation) or 'different structures that result from changes to a common base structure' (sub-networks of state sequences) or 'different interface structures sorted by probability where higher distance is lower probability or where adjacence indicates high probability of co-occurrence' (probable variable network).
These graphs enable queries like 'find different structures in which a variable can vary across interfaces' and 'what unit level to apply so that two independent variables can be connected using combinations/sequences/networks of that unit'.
